               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="perg">
                        <support><material>Parchment</material>.</support>
                        <extent>58 leaves (57 + a fragment). <dimensions type="leaf" scope="all"
                              unit="mm">
                              <height unit="mm">ca. 380</height>
                              <width unit="mm">ca. 280</width>
                           </dimensions>.</extent>
                        <foliation>Modern foliation.</foliation>
                        <condition>The manuscript consists of fragments previously serving as
                           binding for various manuscripts which have been identified and put
                           together. All of the leaves are trimmed which means that the inner
                           margins of most of the leaves are missing, often resulting in a loss of
                           text.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1"><p>Written by two scribes, each of them have applied a
                              separate size of written area and thus a separate number of lines per
                              page.</p>
                           <p>Part I: On fols <locus from="1r" to="15r">1r-15r</locus> and <locus
                                 from="39r:19" to="58v">39r:19-58v</locus> the written area measures
                                 <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                                 <height unit="mm">280/290</height>
                                 <width unit="mm">190/195</width>
                              </dimensions> and there are 32 lines or 16 staffs per page.</p>
                           <p>Part II: On fols <locus from="15v" to="39r:19">15v-39r:19</locus> the
                              written area measures <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                                 <height unit="mm">265/270</height>
                                 <width unit="mm">175/185</width>
                              </dimensions> and the pages have 38 lines or 16 staffs per page.</p>
                           <p>Fols <locus from="15v" to="15v">15v</locus> and <locus from="39r"
                                 to="39r">39r</locus>, however, have 29 lines per page, while <locus
                                 from="17r" to="17r">17r</locus>, <locus from="18r" to="18r"
                                 >18r</locus>, <locus from="24v" to="24v">24v</locus> and <locus
                                 from="26v" to="26v">26v</locus> have 27 lines per page.</p>
                           <p>Pricking in the outer margins can be seen where whole leaves are
                              preserved.</p></layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary>Written by two scribes, both called Jón Þorláksson. See <bibl><ref
                              target="GuðKri2016a">Guðbjörg Kristjánsdóttir
                        2016</ref></bibl>.</summary>
                     <handNote medium="ink" scope="major" script="textualis">The first hand, Jón í
                        Langeyjarnesi, worked as a scribe in the period <date notBefore="1450"
                           notAfter="1478">c. 1450-1478</date>. He wrote fols <locus from="1r"
                           to="15r">1r-15r</locus> and <locus from="41r" to="58v">41r-58v</locus>.
                        He also added some corrections and wrote the rubrics of fols
                        15v-58v.</handNote>
                     <handNote medium="ink" scope="minor" script="textualis">The other scribe, Jón á
                        Hóli, wrote fols <locus from="15v" to="40v">15v-40v</locus>.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <musicNotation><p>Part I (<locus from="1r" to="15r">1r-15r</locus>, <locus
                           from="39r:19" to="58v">39r:19-58v</locus>): Square notation in black
                        four-line staves with a clef; <locus from="40v" to="41v">40v-41v</locus>,
                        however have a square notation in red four-line staves with a clef.</p>
                     <p>Part II (<locus from="15v" to="39r:19">15v-39r:19</locus>): Square notation
                        in red four-line staves with a clef. Recitation: c + s.</p></musicNotation>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="initial" subtype="flourished">On fol. <locus from="6r" to="6r"
                           >6r</locus> a red, green and golden initial (six lines) featuring a
                        palmette in red and blue is found.</decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="initial" subtype="illuminated">On fol. <locus from="15v"
                           to="15v">15v</locus> a large <term>littera florissa</term> in ten lines
                        with foliage in gold, red, green and azure is found.</decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="initial" subtype="flourished"><p>Part I features green, blue,
                           red, ruby or gold lombards in one to five lines. Several have palmettes
                           in a contrasting colour.</p>
                        <p>Part II has gold, blue, green or red lombards taking up two to five
                           lines.</p></decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="secondary">Red line fillers and rubrics.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>Instructions for rubrication can still be seen in the
                     margins.</additions>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>The missal is written in <origPlace>Skarð á Skarðarströnd in Dalasýsla,
                        Iceland</origPlace> (hence the name <title type="uniform">Missale
                        Scardense</title>) in <origDate notBefore="1450" notAfter="1475">the third
                        quarter of the 15th centry</origDate>.</origin>
               </history>
